entity.name: Diego Rivera
entity.text: James D. Cockcroft’s Diego Rivera is a delightful biography describing the life of the great Mexican artist Diego María Rivera. It is part of a series of books entitled Hispanics of Achievement that seeks to describe contributions of great Hispanics both to American society and worldwide. The biography is divided into nine chapters, each a well-illustrated vignette describing a portion of the life and work of the artist. All the chapters, except for chapter 1, are in chronological order. [...] Diego Rivera, a renowned Mexican artist and muralist, is the central figure in a biography that highlights his significant contributions to art and social consciousness. This biography chronicles Rivera's life from his childhood in Mexico through his artistic development in Europe and his eventual return to Mexico, where he became a prominent figure in the Mexican muralism movement. Key moments include his controversial mural at Rockefeller Center in New York, which sparked a notable conflict [...] Rivera's artistic journey is interwoven with his political beliefs, showcasing his leftist ideologies that were influenced by the socio-political climate of Mexico during his formative years. His relationships, especially with fellow artist Frida Kahlo and other partners, are explored, illustrating his complex personal life alongside his artistic pursuits. The biography provides a balanced view of Rivera, depicting him as a passionate individual dedicated to advocating for the dignity of the
